Freshwater benthic organisms are abundant and diverse. They regulate major ecosystem processes (

) and play an important ecological role in detrital food webs (

; Schmid & Schmid-Araya, 2002). However, there is still a debate as to what are the mechanisms determining benthos community structure. 

showed that abiotic factors (oxygen, sediment granulometry, resources) are important in determining the distribution of animals. In contrast, 

suggested that primary productivity and the availability and quality of organic matter influence benthic invertebrate community composition. In benthic communities, the high species richness leads to a large number of biotic interactions and trophic links (

; Schmid & Schmid-Araya, 2002). Studies on the effect of biotic factors, such as competition and predation, are controversial. In lotic habitats, there is little evidence that competition between benthic invertebrates influences the overall distribution patterns; however, it may play a role for some taxa (

). Predation can have a strong (positive and negative) effect on meiofauna distribution in some freshwater systems (

). Besides the effects on species composition, these interactions may also affect the diversity within species because in changing environments they promote the production of genetically variable offspring through sexual reproduction in facultative parthenogenetic species (

). The relationship between competition and investment in sexual reproduction was shown experimentally (

) and theoretically (

; 

). Sex-ratio variation among families is known from several invertebrate taxa (

; 

) but has not yet generally been established for aquatic groups. However, 

demonstrated the relationship between competition and the investment in sexual reproduction for pelagic rotifers. They showed that competitive displacement between rotifer species was related to a higher investment in sexual reproduction by the displaced species.

For studying community patterns of benthic invertebrates, alpine lakes of central Europe provide an ideal study system. They are well-defined small habitats, have similar environmental conditions, and are almost unaffected by human activity. Only a small number of ecological and taxonomic studies have focused on the alpine region (
e.g.,

; 

, b; 

). Most studies have been restricted to the macrofauna (organisms which are retained on a net with a mesh size of 500 
µ
m), while the meiofauna (organisms which are retained on a net with a mesh size of about 40 
µ
m) has received less attention; moreover, much less is known of the most abundant and species rich taxa – the nematodes.

The calculation of nematode biomass was based on 

. Males, females, and two categories of juveniles (stages 4 and 1-3) were treated separately. For all other invertebrates 20 individuals per taxon and per lake were measured (body length, diam.) to the nearest 
µ
m, using calibrated Zeiss image analysis software (KS300 3.0). Body volume of ostracods, copepods, gastrotrichs, tardigrades and oligochaetes was derived from measurements using the formula of Feller and Warwick (1992). Rotifers were assumed to be ellipsoid/oval (

). Their body volume was multiplied by an average density (1.13 g/cm 
3
) and a dry/wet ratio of 0.25 to obtain dry weight biomass (

). For chironomids and nauplii (Crustacea: Copepoda), measurements were converted to dry weight using published regression equations (

).

