Tylencholaimus sp.
) were less common. The large omnivores contributed most (53-90%) to nematode biomass in all lakes, except for Vilsalpsee and Schmalsee where epistrate feeders dominated (44-47%).

Nematodes were the most numerous invertebrate group in most alpine lakes and accounted for up to 90% of the benthic community. This result is supported by other studies which showed that nematodes dominate the lake benthos, followed by rotifers, oligochaetes and crustaceans (review in 

). The lakes showed similar values in oxygen content, nitrogen and phosphate. However, there was an increase in benthic abundance with increasing organic carbon content and no other relationship between other abiotic parameters and benthos abundance or biomass was found. This wide range in benthic densities (100-740 individuals/cm 
2
) and the diverse taxa composition between lakes could be due to varying biotic factors. The spatial variability of benthic communities is known to be largely dependent upon changes in food quality and quantity (

). Sampling was carried out at the beginning of the alpine spring season when resources were probably a limiting factor. Food competition between nematodes, tardigrades and rotifers, and predation by nematodes, tardigrades, crustaceans, planarians and macro-invertebrate taxa are assumed to have a strong influence on population densities (

; 

; 

; 

). In our field study, the negative relationships between nematodes and ostracods, as well as between tardigrades and crustaceans, are unlikely to be attributed to food competition. The positive relationship within crustaceans and between crustaceans and oligochaetes and chironomids may indicate that all these groups were equally affected by the availability of food. It can only be speculated whether competition or predation affected these patterns.

The nematode assemblages showed a varying pattern in terms of species composition, species richness and diversity among the 11 alpine lakes. Many of the abundant species found in these alpine lakes, are common species in freshwater habitats on several continents (

; 

; 

). However, some of the most abundant species (

Prodesmodora circulata

, 

Rhabdolaimus terrestris

, 

Ethmolaimus pratensis

) are typical of oligotrophic habitats (

). This is supported by the Shannon-Wiener diversity index found in the alpine lakes. 

showed that the species diversity of nematodes decreases with the advancement of lakes trophy. According to 

, Wildensee, Schmalsee and Lautersee would be classified as mesotrophic.

In the investigated lakes, an increase of species richness was related to: 
i
) an increase of nematode sex-ratio; and 
ii
) to a decrease of the proportion of parthenogenetic species in the most abundant feeding type. Sexuality (reflecting high genetic variability) is favoured in areas of high biotic complexity, whereas asexuals (producing more offspring) persist only in disclimax habitats (Red Queen hypothesis; 

). Alpine nematode assemblages were dominated by (facultative) parthenogenetic species, as in other freshwater habitats (
e.g
., 

; 

). Parthenogenesis may be of an advantage for colonising isolated habitats, such as alpine lakes. A clear dominance of parthenogenetic reproduction seems to be a more widespread pattern in freshwater systems. In contrast to marine environments where sexual reproduction predominates, nematodes, tardigrades and ostracods reproduce mainly parthenogenetically in fresh water (

; 

; 

). Some benthic and zooplanktonic groups show that interspecific interactions favour genetic diversity. In most species of the cladoceran 

Daphnia

, parthenogenesis occurs when conditions are favourable for growth while sexual reproduction is stimulated by unfavourable conditions, such as high population density and interspecific competition (

). In ostracods and in zooplanktonic rotifers, the degree of environmental stress directly controls the mode of reproduction (

; 

).
